Part I - Prosper Loan Dataset Exploration¶

by Rawand Radi¶

Introduction¶

The Prosper dataset contains information about loans originated through the Prosper peer-to-peer lending platform. The dataset includes detailed loan information such as loan terms, interest rates, borrower credit information, income details, and loan status. It consists of 113,937 observations and 81 variables.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • The cleaned dataset contains 77,557 rows and 13 columns.

  • It includes numeric, categorical, and boolean data types.

  • Key columns retained are related to loan details and borrower information, such as BorrowerAPR, ProsperRating (Alpha), ProsperScore, IncomeRange, StatedMonthlyIncome, LoanOriginalAmount, Term, LoanStatus, EmploymentStatus, DebtToIncomeRatio, CreditScoreRangeLower, CreditScoreRangeUpper, and IsBorrowerHomeowner.

  • All rows with missing values in these columns were dropped to ensure clean and complete data for analysis.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  1. The main feature of interest is BorrowerAPR, which represents the annual percentage rate assigned to a borrower. I want to explore what factors contribute to a higher or lower APR.

  2. LoanStatus : to understand the risk associated with loans.

  3. ProsperRating : to evaluate how credit ratings influence loan terms.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

ProsperRating (Alpha) and ProsperScore (borrower risk)

IncomeRange and StatedMonthlyIncome (financial capacity)

EmploymentStatus (employment stability)

DebtToIncomeRatio (debt burden)

CreditScoreRangeLower and CreditScoreRangeUpper (creditworthiness)

LoanOriginalAmount and Term (loan characteristics)

IsBorrowerHomeowner (financial reliability)

IncomeRange - Count Plot : What is the distribution of income ranges in the dataset?¶

In [14]:
unique_ranges = df_clean['IncomeRange'].dropna().unique()

def income_sort_key(val):
    if val == 'Not employed':
        return 0
    elif val == '$0':
        return 1
    elif '-' in val:
        return int(val.replace('$', '').replace(',', '').split('-')[0])
    elif '$100,000+' in val:
        return 100000
    elif 'Not displayed' in val:
        return float('inf')  
    else:
        return np.nan
In [17]:
sorted_income_ranges = sorted(unique_ranges, key=income_sort_key, reverse=True)

LoanStatus-Count Plot¶

In [18]:
statuses = df_clean['LoanStatus'].dropna().unique()

def loan_status_rank(status):
    status = status.lower()
    if 'current' in status:
        return 0
    elif 'completed' in status:
        return 1
    elif 'finalpayment' in status:
        return 2
    elif 'past due' in status:
        # Extract day range, "1-15" or ">120"
        import re
        match = re.search(r'(\d+)', status)
        if match:
            return 3 + int(match.group(1))  # rank based on days
        elif '>120' in status:
            return 10_000
        else:
            return 9999
    elif 'charged' in status:
        return 999_999
    elif 'default' in status:
        return 1_000_000
    else:
        return np.inf

sorted_statuses = sorted(statuses, key=loan_status_rank)
In [19]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
sns.countplot(data=df_clean, x='LoanStatus', color='tab:blue', order=sorted_statuses)
plt.title('Distribution of Loan Status')
plt.xticks(rotation=15)
plt.xlabel('Loan Status')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The most common loan status is Current, followed by Completed. There are smaller groups like Chargedoff, Defaulted, which may be useful for analyzing default risk later.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of BorrowerAPR is right-skewed, with most values between 0.1 and 0.25. A few higher values above 0.35 exist but are expected for high-risk borrowers. No transformation was needed at this stage.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Some features like StatedMonthlyIncome were highly skewed due to a few large values. I didn’t remove them, but I limited the axis in plots for better visibility. I also dropped rows with missing values to keep the dataset clean and consistent for analysis.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

BorrowerAPR was lower for borrowers with higher Prosper Ratings and Income Ranges. It didn’t change much with Debt-to-Income Ratio or Stated Monthly Income. The clearest pattern was: better credit = lower APR.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Yes, an interesting relationship was observed between Loan Term and Loan Status. Longer terms (60 months) had a noticeably higher number of Charged-off loans compared to shorter terms (36 months), suggesting a higher risk with extended loan durations.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Yes, Prosper Score and Prosper Rating both affect Borrower APR. Higher scores and better ratings mean lower APRs. Income also matters, but even with similar incomes, better scores lead to lower APRs. So, these features together help explain APR better.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Yes, even borrowers with similar incomes had different APRs depending on their Prosper Score or Rating. This shows that creditworthiness affects APR more than income alone, which was interesting to see.

Conclusions¶

The dataset contains detailed loan and borrower information from Prosper, with 113,937 entries and 81 variables, but many missing values required cleaning.

The main focus was on Borrower APR, investigating what influences loan interest rates.

Key features influencing APR include Prosper Rating (Alpha), Prosper Score, Income Range, Stated Monthly Income, Debt-to-Income Ratio, and Loan Term.

Borrowers with higher credit ratings and scores consistently receive lower APRs, showing a strong inverse relationship between creditworthiness and interest rates.

Income impacts APR but less strongly than credit ratings; borrowers with similar incomes may still have different APRs depending on their credit scores.

Debt-to-Income Ratio has a mild effect on APR, with slightly higher APRs for borrowers with very high DTI.

Longer loan terms (e.g., 60 months) have a higher proportion of charged-off or defaulted loans, indicating increased risk with longer loans.

Multivariate analysis revealed that combining features like Prosper Score, Prosper Rating, and Income gives a better understanding of APR variations than looking at any single feature alone.

Data cleaning steps, including removing rows with missing values and limiting outliers, ensured accurate and reliable analysis.

Overall, creditworthiness metrics are the strongest predictors of loan interest rates on the Prosper platform, more so than income or debt alone.
